@NODE "Usage" "How to use ModemActivator!"

                             @{b}@{u}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

Quick instruction on how to use ModemActivator!

Installation:
Put MA in your 'WBStartup' drawer [Remember the Icon]!

@{u}Usage:@{uu}

ModemActivator doesn't use a config.file to store the config. All information
is stored in the Icon!! Remember this!!

The icon contains multiple tooltypes. Here is an snapshot of the tooltypes
from my configuration:

FILE=Miami:Miami
SMARTMODE=ON
DEVICENAME=serial.device
UNIT=0
DONOTWAIT

Lets have a look at the tooltypes, and what they do:

@{u}'FILE=Miami:Miami'@{uu}

This tooltype contains the path plus name of the program to be run, upon
modem activation. This can be script if you like it! Just remember to set
the '+s' bit!! Also notice that names like 'Ram Disk:nukewin.exe' is not
accepted. No space is allowed in the drivename!!

Please notice, that you can only state ONE[1] file to be executed. If you
want more files to be executed, make a script and make MA execute it for you!


@{u}'SMARTMODE=ON'@{uu}

This tooltype tells MA if smartmode should be enabled or not! Smartmode is
a mode, where MA stays online constantly. It will try to monitor your
modem.device every user given interval[in seconds], even if if can't open
the device. When you turn on your modem, MA will react by running your
program/script. Then it will wait for your modem to turn off again. When MA
has detected you modem is turned off, it will wait for it to be turned on
again. When this happen, it will run your selected program/script again!
This loop will go on forever and ever, unless you tell MA to go
inactive [eg. via Exchange].

When Smartmode is turned off [by writing off, or deleting the tooltype], MA
will go inactive before running your program. Then you will have to put MA
online again by yourself [Exchange].

When using Smartmode, please notice that the device is only checked every
user given interval[off and on]!!


@{u}'DEVICENAME=serial.device'@{uu}

As the name indicates, this is where you state the name of the device
you use to connect you modem. If none is stated, serial.device is used
as default!!


@{u}'UNIT=0'@{uu}

This is the unit of the device to check!! If your modem is on unit 2, the
tooltype will look like this 'UNIT=2'. If none is stated, the default is '0'.


@{u}'TIME=5'@{uu}

This tooltype tells MACT how often to check your modem. Don't set it below
3-5, as MACT would begin to steal TOO much system time! Upper limit is 999
seconds! TIME will affect every timing in the program.


@{u}'DONOTWAIT'@{uu}

DON'T DELETE THIS TOOLTYPE!!! It tells Workbench not to wait for MA to
return!! If you delete it, Workbench WILL complain!!


All settings can be changed either with the commodity interface, or by hand!!


                              @{b}@{u}Error Hunting@{ub}@{uu}

If nothing happends when you turn on you modem, there are several
possibilities to what could have gone wrong:

-The program you have chosen does not excist!
-The program you have chosen could not be run!
-MACT haven't detected you modem! Try setting "FORCE DSR SIGNAL HIGH (ALWAYS)"
 Look in your modem user manual for instructions!
 If it still doesn't work, contact @{"me!" link "contact"}
-You are using another device than seriel.device, and you have tried setting
 the "FORCE DSR SIGNAL HIGH" hint, contact me and tell what device you use!
-You have tryed installing the program on a WinTel machine, but the program
 just wont work: Chain you WinTel machine to your right foot, AND THROW
 YOUR PC OUT THE WINDOW!! :-)
-Contact me with a detailed error report!(done this/tryed to.../patches)


SSD98
@EndNode


